+# tablesmith
+
+A lightweight, scriptable pipeline engine for tabular data. Think *csvkit
+meets unix pipes*, but as a single tool with a proper pipeline model.
+
+- **Zero dependencies** — pure Python standard library (3.8+).
+- **CSV, JSON, JSONL** — any of them in, any of them out.
+- **Chainable operations** — filter, select/rename, sort, group+aggregate,
+  join, compute, distinct, limit, drop.
+- **Two modes** — quick inline flags for one-liners, or a JSON pipeline file
+  for repeatable multi-step transforms.
+- **Automatic type inference** — numbers are numbers, you don’t declare
+  schemas.
+- **Useful errors** — tells you *which step*, *which column*, and usually
+  *what you probably meant*.
+
+## Install
+
+```bash
+pip install .
+tablesmith --version
+# or without installing:
+python -m tablesmith --help
+```
+
+## Quick start (inline flags)
+
+Operations are applied **in the order they appear on the command line**, so
+you can chain freely:
+
+```bash
+tablesmith people.csv \
+    --filter 'age >= 30 and dept == "eng"' \
+    --compute 'bonus = round(salary * 0.10)' \
+    --select 'name,dept,salary,bonus' \
+    --sort 'salary:desc' \
+    -F json
+```
+
+Reading from stdin / writing to stdout is the default (`-` means stdin):
+
+```bash
+cat events.jsonl | tablesmith - -i jsonl \
+    --filter 'status != "ok"' \
+    --group 'service:count(),max(latency_ms)' \
+    -o errors.csv
+```
+
+## Pipeline files
+
+For anything you’ll run more than once, put it in a JSON file:
+
+```json
+{
+  "input": "people.csv",
+  "steps": [
+    {"op": "filter",  "expr": "salary > 80000"},
+    {"op": "join",    "path": "depts.json", "on": "dept", "how": "left"},
+    {"op": "compute", "column": "bonus", "expr": "round(salary * 0.1)"},
+    {"op": "select",  "columns": ["name", "dept", "location", "salary", "bonus"]},
+    {"op": "sort",    "by": "salary", "desc": true}
+  ],
+  "output": {"path": "report.csv", "format": "csv"}
+}
+```
+
+```bash
+tablesmith -p transform.json
+tablesmith -p transform.json --explain     # print the resolved pipeline
+```
+
+CLI flags override file `input`/`output`, and any inline `--filter` / `--sort`
+etc. are appended *after* the file’s steps — handy for ad-hoc tweaks.
+
+## Operations
+
+| op | inline syntax | notes |
+|---|---|---|
+| `filter` / `where` | `--filter 'age > 30 and city == "NYC"'` | full expression language (see below) |
+| `select` / `cols` | `--select 'id,name:full_name,age'` | rename with `old:new` or `old AS new` |
+| `rename` | `--rename 'dept:department'` | keeps all other columns |
+| `drop` | `--drop 'ssn,password'` | |
+| `sort` / `order` | `--sort 'dept,salary:desc'` or `--sort=-salary` | `-col` / `col:desc` for descending |
+| `group` / `agg` | `--group 'dept:avg(salary) as avg,count()'` | aggs: `sum avg mean median min max count first last list nunique` |
+| `join` | `--join 'other.csv on user_id=id how left prefix r_'` | `inner` (default) / `left` / `right` / `outer` |
+| `compute` / `add` | `--compute 'total = price * qty'` | add/overwrite a derived column |
+| `distinct` / `unique` | `--distinct` or `--distinct 'email'` | |
+| `limit` / `head` | `--limit 10` or `--limit 10,5` | N or N,OFFSET |
+
+## Expression language
+
+Used by `filter` and `compute`. Column names are bare identifiers.
+
+```
+==  !=  <  <=  >  >=  in  not in
+and  or  not
++  -  *  /  //  %  **      (ternary)  a if cond else b
+len abs round min max str int float bool
+lower upper strip startswith endswith contains matches coalesce
+```
+
+```bash
+--filter 'status in ("open","pending") and not startswith(name, "test_")'
+--compute 'domain = lower(email)'
+```
+
+Expressions are parsed with Python’s `ast` and evaluated against a strict
+whitelist — no attribute access, no imports, no `__dunder__` escapes.
+
+## I/O
+
+| flag | meaning |
+|---|---|
+| `input` (positional) | path or `-` for stdin |
+| `-o, --output` | path or `-` for stdout |
+| `-i, --input-format` | `csv` / `json` / `jsonl` (auto-detected from extension otherwise) |
+| `-F, --output-format` | same |
+| `--delimiter` | override CSV delimiter (auto-sniffed by default; `.tsv` ⇒ tab) |
+| `--no-infer` | keep CSV cells as raw strings |
+
+JSON input may be an array of objects, a single object, or a
+`{"data": [...]}`‑style wrapper. JSONL is one object per line.
+
+## Errors that actually help
+
+```text
+$ tablesmith people.csv --filter 'agee > 10'
+tablesmith: error (step #1 [filter]): unknown column 'agee'
+  hint: did you mean 'age'?
+
+$ tablesmith people.csv --group 'dept:summ(salary)'
+tablesmith: error (step #1 [group]): unknown aggregate 'summ'
+  hint: available: avg, count, first, last, list, max, mean, median, min, nunique, sum
+```
+
+Add `--debug` to get the underlying Python traceback.
+
+## As a library
+
+```python
+from tablesmith import Pipeline
+from tablesmith.ops import Filter, Sort
+from tablesmith.ioformats import read_rows, write_rows
+
+rows = read_rows("people.csv")
+rows = Pipeline([Filter("age >= 30"), Sort.from_cli("salary:desc")]).run(rows)
+write_rows(rows, "-", "json")
+```
